  <div class="overview row col s12">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="wowHead" id="process"><h2>The Process and Insight</h2></span>
      <div class="stacker">
        <div class="card medium">
         <div class="card-image waves-effect waves-block waves-light">
           <img class="activator" src="../assets/img/Logo.png">
         </div>
         <div class="card-content">
           <span class="card-title activator redText">Mentality<i class="material-icons right">more_vert</i></span>
           <p>Before anything, my design ideals were put to the test with how eclectic Wowhead is. Content is everywhere and anywhere and thinking simplistic proved challenging. </p>
         </div>
         <div class="card-reveal">
           <span class="card-title"><i class="material-icons right">close</i></span>
           <p>Since there was so much information thrown at the user, I drew out several ideas of how to modernize and simplify it. I wanted to maintain the World of Warcraft theme so in order to do that, I kept the similar text and text colors. Gradients galore! I fell in love with gradients while using Sketch, with that it gave components a more 3D feel to it.</p>
           <p>The logo they had used was a red rocket grinning. Personally, I'm not exactly sure what the relevance was with World of Warcraft. I decided to recreate a logo more fitting to the redesign with a more sleek and modern one. Since Wowhead is the most used database for the video game, it seemed fitting to incorporate the original World of Warcraft logo and combined it with the title of the website.</p>
         </div>
        </div>
        <div class="card medium">
          <div class="card-image waves-effect waves-block waves-light">
            <img class="activator" src="../assets/img/ClassGuidesMenu.png">
          </div>
          <div class="card-content">
            <span class="card-title activator redText">Atomic Thinking<i class="material-icons right">more_vert</i></span>
            <p>Using my newfound knowledge of the atomic process. I broke down components of Wowhead into componets that could be used multiple times.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card-reveal">
            <span class="card-title"><i class="material-icons right">close</i></span>
            <p>I spent at least an hour staring and navigating through the layout of Wowhead. I clicked through several pages of information taking note of key items used. </p>

            <p>Examples included: navigation, buttons, boxes of text information, hover effects, etc. Starting with navigation, I created several symbols within Sketch and was easily able to plant them throughout my layout which saved a ton of time.</p>
          </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card medium">
           <div class="card-image waves-effect waves-block waves-light">
             <img class="activator" src="../assets/img/QuestModal.png">
           </div>
           <div class="card-content">
             <span class="card-title activator redText">Usability<i class="material-icons right">more_vert</i></span>
             <p>The biggest challenge with this redesign was the usability. Wowhead has over ten years of accumulated information from users all across the globe. </p>
           </div>
           <div class="card-reveal">
             <span class="card-title"><i class="material-icons right">close</i></span>
             <p>The sheer amount of information that Wowhead has is overwhelming. As I spent my time navigating and noticing where they chose to place information, it was a lot to take in. As noisy as it was with information laid out in every possible crevice of the DOM, I managed to pin point the most important parts of each section.</p>
             <p>In order to condense the amount of information being thrown at the user, I had to think of it from my own perspective. As a user, a player of this game, what is it that I mainly use this website for? I developed three personas, whom were actually real people I've known to use Wowhead and thought about how they might use it.</p>
             <p>Going with my simplistic approach, I developed pathways that lead the user to the least amount of clicking but with the maximum condensed amount of information. The use of modals was key.</p>
           </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

